Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.

                      output cout,

Checking if done:

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.

                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.

  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

Best terminal state. Max tokens:  1024

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.

                      input cin);

  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.

  //obtain four intermediate results.

  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.

  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.

  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.

                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);

  //first use two 32 bit adders to compute the carry bits
  //32-bit adder 1
  adder_32 add1_1(sum[31:0], c1, in1[31:0], in2[31:0], cin);

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);

  //first use two 32 bit adders to compute the carry bits
  //32-bit adder 1

  //32-bit adder 2
  adder_32 add2_1(sum[63:32], c2, in1[63:32], in2[63:32], 1'b0);

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.

                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);

endmodule

//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.

MCTS Stage 2 - Expansion: next action:  4  corresponding to state:  [[   16   290   287    17    13   198 50286  1003    66   448]]

MCTS Stage 3 - Rollout: Getting rollout return of leaf.

Best terminal state. Max tokens:  1024
init state length =  133
current state length =  163
Checking if done:
tokens generated:  30
Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.

//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is calculated as in1 + in2 + cin
  //cout is calculated as in1[63] + in2[63] + cin
  assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  wire [63:0] sum_temp;
  wire [63:0] carry;
  genvar i;
  generate
    for(i=0; i<64; i=i+1)
      begin: generate_adder
        if(i==0) half_adder f(sum_temp[0], carry[0], in1[0], in2[0]);
        else full_adder f(sum_temp[i], carry[i], in1[i], in2[i], carry[i-1]);
      end
    assign sum = sum_temp;
    assign cout = carry[63];
  endgenerate
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  wire [63:0] sum_temp;
  wire [63:0] carry;
  genvar i;
  generate
    for(i=0; i<64; i=i+1)
      begin: generate_adder
        if(i==0) half_adder f(sum_temp[0], carry[0], in1[0], in2[0]);
        else full_adder f(sum_temp[i], carry[i], in1[i], in2[i], carry[i-1]);
      end
    assign sum = sum_temp;
    assign cout = carry[63];
  endgenerate
endmodule

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
  //design implementation
  //sum is a 64 bit variable that holds the sum of in1 and in2.
  //cout is a single bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //To add the two inputs, in1 and in2, the inputs are first processed to
  //obtain four intermediate results.
  //The first step is to break down the 64 bit inputs into two 32 bit inputs,
  //in1_hi and in1_lo.
  //The second step is to break down the 32 bit inputs, in2_hi and in2_lo.
  //The final step is to obtain the sum of the two 32 bit inputs.
  //This is done by using the 32 bit adder module.
  //The carry-out value is also obtained by using the 32 bit adder.
  //The carry-in value is set to zero.
  assign in1_hi = in1[63:32];
  assign in1_lo = in1[31:0];
  assign in2_hi = in2[63:32];
  assign in2_lo = in2[31:0];
  assign sum[63:32] = in1_hi + in2_hi;
  assign sum[31:0] = in1_lo + in2_lo;
  assign cout = in1_hi + in2_hi + cin;
endmodule

Calling isPromptComplete: 
original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    /* write your code here */
    genvar i;
    assign c[0] = cin;
    generate for(i = 0; i < 64; i = i + 1)
    begin
        if(i == 0)
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i]);
        else
            full_adder fa(sum[i], c[i+1], in1[i], in2[i], c[i-1]);
    end
    endgenerate
    assign cout = c[64];
    /* write your code here */
endmodule

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule

//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.

original text:  //Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);

  //cout is a 1 bit variable that holds the carry-out value.
  //in1 and in2 are 64 bit variables that hold the two 64 bit inputs.

//Design a 64-bit adder.
//There are two 64 bit inputs (in1 and in2) and a single carry-in input bit, cin.
//The outputs are a 64 bit value, [63:0] sum, and a single carry-out output bit, cout.
//The module should utilize the inputs (in1 and in2) and the cin bit to obtain the output sum and cout values.
module adder_64(output [63:0] sum,
                      output cout,
                      input [63:0] in1, in2,
                      input cin);
    assign {cout, sum} = in1 + in2 + cin;
endmodule
